defaultThe scope for varying the current mix of service responsibilities so that more people are treated outside hospital and the consequences of such service re-design for costs and effectivenessdefault2.1
default defaultBoth the Health
default Committee
default and the National Audit Office
default have previously pointed out
default 
defaultthat the more appropriate use of 
defaultacute 
defaulthospital services is critical for the future achievement of efficiency savings. To achieve this, effective community health services are important, as is 
defaultthe quality of 
defaultprimary care.
default 
defaultOne important gauge of these services’ effect on the health system are rates of admissions for
default 
default 
default 
default‘ambulatory care sensitive conditions (ACS) - 
defaultclinical conditions for which the risk of emergency admission can be reduced by timely and effective ambulatory care, meaning mainly primary care, community
default and social
default services
default,
default and outpatient care. 
default2.2 
defaultA 2013 Nuffield Trust observational study of 
defaulthospital admission data spanning the period between
default March 2001 to April 2011 reveal
defaulted
default that the number of emergency admissions per year for ACS conditions 
defaulthad
default increased over the decade by 40%, rising from 701 995 admissions per year to 982 482 annually.
default 
defaultEmergency admissions for ACS conditions were more common among the oldest and youngest age groups 
defaultWhen the age-standardised rates of emergency admissions for ACS conditions were compared, the overall increase was 25% indicating that 
defaultnot all of th
defaulte decade long
default rise in
default 
default 
default 
defaultadmission rates 
defaultwas
default due 
defaultto the changing demographic structure of the population. The
default overall trend
default also
default 
defaultmasked differences between the three broad categories of ACS conditions (acute, chronic and vaccine preventable).
default 
default 
default 
defaultFor acute ACS conditions the age standardised rate of increase was 44%, while vaccine preventable rates (such as for influenza) went up by 136%, albeit from a much smaller base.
default2.3 
defaultT
defaulthe rate of admissions for chronic ACS conditions held roughly 
defaultsteady. Among
default th
defaultis group
default,
default the conditions
default with the highest rises in the absolute numbers of admissions were chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and convulsions and epilepsy. 
defaultThe number of admissions for diabetes grew by 95% and contributed an extra 16 996 admissions. Meanwhile 
defaultage-standardised
default rates of admissions for congestive heart failure and angina showed marked and significant reductions (--27%
default and -41% respectively
default). 
default2.4 
defaultThere are a number of possible 
defaultexplanations 
defaultfor
default the observed increases in 
defaultthe chronic group of 
defaultACS admissions. For some ACS conditions changes could be due to the differences in the underlying prevalence of disease; changes in health
default-
defaultrelated behaviours such as smoking or improvements in the effectiveness of treatments for 
defaultsome 
defaultdiseases for example, statins for angina. 
defaultOther possible 
defaultexplanations 
defaultinclude 
defaultchanges in the way health systems operate
default, for example changes in the thresholds for admission to hospital. 
defaultI
defaultt
default 
defaultmay be 
defaultthe case that patients admitted now are less sick than they were 10 years ago
default, as 
defaultsuggested 
defaultby the rise in short stay admissions and lower rates of mortality shown in an earlier Nuffield Trust study
default.
default 
defaultOr
default that admission decisions are in part influenced by the perceived lack of alternatives to inpatient care
default (for example an absence of social care or community based alternatives to hospital)
default.
default  
default 
default2.5 
defaultSome caution is required
default as the
default evidence connecting the rising trend
default in ACS admissions
default to specific policies is weak. 
defaultFor example the introduction of the 4 hour A&amp;E target and changes to the GP out of hours contract (both in 2004) are commonly cited as increasing the overall level of emergency admissions, yet our study suggests that emergency admissions continued 
defaulton 
defaultan 
defaultunderlying upward 
defaulttrend at this point, with no obvious 
defaultacceleration 
defaultin
default the rates of
default 
defaultACS 
defaulto
defaultr non-ACS
default emergency
default admissions. Indeed
default some of the more common ACS conditions show trends that closely mirror the rise in rates of emergency admission for non-ACS conditions. This suggests that the organisation and financing of the health system itself are perhaps more important determinants than the changing health needs of the population over the decade
default- specifically the expansion of acute sector capacity from 2002
default.
default We know from the consolidated NHS accounts that community health services have experienced particularly rapid growth in spending since 2006/07. Acute spending also continues to increase but spending on primary care, and in particular GP services, has been falling in recent years
default in real terms
default.
