default3. 6
default defaultA key 
defaultdeterminant
default 
defaultwill 
defaultinvolve the extent to which commissioners are supported to balance the possible tensions that can arise when policies in support of competition and choice (and the associated procurement laws) interact with the planned shift to greater 
defaultcoordination of 
defaultcommunity based 
defaultservices. These ought not to be mutually exclusive policies but in practice
default  
default 
defaultthere is a risk that the scope for regulatory action is perceived by commissioners as potentially
default  
default 
defaultbeing so wide and far reaching that it inhibits service redesign and innovation. Second, those commissioners wanting to redesign services appear to be faced with a high burden of proof. Emerging Competition and Cooperation panel guidance
default suggests
default that commissioners and providers will have to show that their actions produce benefits that are ‘significant, quantifiable and evidence based’ to set against the theoretical costs of any reductions in competition and patient choice.
default This is a high threshold of evidence to meet, particularly when the effects of large scale integrated care projects can take several years to emerge fully. 
defaultThe practical assistance offered to commissioners todefault support the design of services defaultwhich promote community-based care and provide for the integration of health and social care in the management of long-term conditionsdefault4.1
default defaultEarlier this year the Nuffield Trust published a major
default National Institute of Health Research-funded
default study exploring
default w
defaulthat commissioners actually do when
default commission
defaulting
default care for people with long-term conditions, and how this might be improved.
default The research was based on 15 months of detailed observation from November 2010 to January 2012 in three commissioning communities: Calderdale, Somerset and the Wirral. These sites were selected because on various indicators they appeared to be at the forefront of commissioning practice. 
defaultT
defaulthe research focused on the commissioning of care for people with long-term conditions: diabetes in all three sites (to allow comparison), and a second condition chosen by each primary care trust: dementia in Calderdale and the Wirral, and stroke in Somerset.
default4.2
default defaultA huge amount of effort was observed going into commissioning across all six service developments, in terms of strategic planning, service review, and hands-on work (typically by middle managers within primary care trusts) to implement and support change.
default The research further revealed that the commissioning 
defaultwas not seen 
defaultas a two-sided transaction across the ‘purchaser–provider split’, at least where long-term conditions are concerned. Local commissioners were instead developing an alternative approach based on c
defaultollaborative 
defaultworking between providers and commissioners.
default 
default 
default 
defaultWhile there are clear benefits to this, in terms of clinicians driving change, there are also risks; including potential conflicts of interest, for example providers using senior clinicians to help ward off cha
defaultllenges from 
defaultcommissioners
default, or providers being actually involved in design of services for which they subsequently tender.
default 
default4.3
default defaultThe study concluded
default defaultthat 
defaultcommissioning is a 
defaultlabor-intensive
default 
defaultactivity
default, often concentrated on relatively marginal rather than mainstream service developments
default.
default 
defaultIt was also noted to be
default much more relational 
defaultthan transactional in nature, with commissioners appearing reluctant to engage in challenge of providers and decommissioning, preferring to focus on service planning and design, involvement and consultation with local stakeholders, and 
defaultimplementation of new developments
default. In the 
defaultnew commissioning system
default, 
defaultgiven 
defaultrecent 
defaultmanagement cost reductions of some 40 per cent, clinical commissioning groups will have to be very selective about how they allocate their time and effort. 
defaultCommissioners’ traditional role of as convenors
default of the local health system
default may also have to adapt, or at the very least be scaled back - they
default will need to be brave enough to ‘cut and run’ and make 
defaultdifficult 
defaultdecision
defaults
default when they feel they have undertaken enough consultation and engagement, even if this flies in the face of NHS (provider and commissioner) culture that favours extensive involvement and consultation as a way of reviewing and making changes to services.
default4.4
default defaultThe implication of this is that done well, commissioning can be a lonely role, especially when it involves the ‘tough work’ of chang
defaulting
default 
default 
default 
defaultservices
default - work
default that 
defaultis
default likely at times to threaten professional and provider interests, or prove unpopular with some in the wider community. 
defaultC
defaultommissioners will need intelligence from commissioning support units to challenge providers on quality and value for money,
default and 
defaultwhere necessary, 
defaultuse procurement to let 
defaultcontracts 
defaultfor 
defaultservices for their populations. This should include high-quality public health and needs assessment advice, sophisticated and real-time data about services, accurate comparisons with national benchmarks, efficient payment and invoicing systems, and support for modelling and planning future care. In addition, 
defaultcommissioners 
defaultwill need support in undertaking 
defaultpublic 
defaultconsultation, accessing and analysing patient and public experience data, providing local system leadership, and handling procurement within a cultural context of collaboration.
defaultThe implications of an ageing population for the prevalence and type of long term conditions, together with evidence about the extent to which existing services will have the capacity to meet future demanddefault5.1
default defaultPopulation growth and demographic change are fundamental drivers of future health care activity. Clearly,
default as a population grows, demands
default for health care will rise. Additionally, a population with a 
defaulthigher
default proportion of older people will have a greater need for health care. While health service utilisation tends to increase with age, t
defaulthere is additional use of 
defaulthealth services as people approach the end of their life
default, regardless of 
defaultage. This increase is less
default 
defaultpronounced for people aged over 85 years, but is still evident. Use of health services is
default 
defaultthus dependent not just on ageing, but also on the number of people who are expected to
default 
defaultdie at any particular time.
default5.2
default defaultOur December 2012 report mapping the medium term NHS productivity challenge used the principal ONS projections from 2008 for population, mortality and fertility to 
defaultcreate a projection to 2021/22.
default The population is projected to grow for all age groups of 50 years and above, for both males
default and females. The probability of having an inpatient admission related to a chronic condition is higher for older age groups than younger age groups. Admissions linked to chronic conditions are therefore likely to rise as the population ages. However, recent trends suggest that this probability is also rising within age bands. If this trend continues, the impact on the NHS due to chronic conditions will amplify the effect of population growth alone.
default5.3
default defaultFor primary care, we examined trends in the number of times a year individuals visit their GP. The number of consultations at a GP practice per person per year rose from 3.9 in 1995/96 to 5.5 in 2008/09. Over the same period, the proportion of these consultations occurring with a GP, rather than a practice nurse, fell from 75 per cent in 1995/96 to 62 per cent in 2008/09. We have assumed that both of these trends will continue over the period 2010/11 to 2021/22, so that by 2021/22 there will be 7.8 consultations per person per year; 55 per cent of which will be with a GP.
default 
defaultWe applied a similar technique to the mental health model to predict how many people would require mental health services each year, based on the number of people using services between 2008/09 and 2010/11. This projection would see the proportion of people aged over 65 years using mental health services growing by just over 50 per cent by 2021/22
default.
default5.4
default defaultFurther protection of the NHS budget is not guaranteed due to the uncertainty of the economic outlook for the country. Our analysis concluded that without unprecedented, sustained increases in health service productivity
default, including more effective management of chronic conditions
default, funding for the NHS in England will need to increase in real terms between 2015/16 and 2021/22 to avoid cuts to the service or a fall in quality. Yet with no clear signs of economic recovery, it is conceivable that NHS funding may be frozen for further years. If this is the case, a major rethink of how health services in England are funded and organised will be needed.
default It is crucial, therefore, that the NHS becomes much better at preventing and managing long-term conditions.
